at you that you don't know, and then you stop listening, and that's no fun.

00:02:26.119 --> 00:02:31.720
So first I'm going to define bi and polypartite networks and networks in general, because

00:02:31.720 --> 00:02:36.559
I'm going to mention them a little bit. So bipartite networks or polypartite networks

00:02:36.559 --> 00:02:40.960
are networks that have nodes of multiple distinct types where connections can't form between

00:02:40.960 --> 00:02:47.520
nodes of the same type. So in this example, we have various pollinators and various flowers.

00:02:47.600 --> 00:02:54.800
And you can draw an edge between a pollinator and a flower based on if that pollinator pollinates

00:02:54.800 --> 00:02:59.160
that flower. So butterflies pollinate lilies and clovers. But you can never have a connection

00:02:59.160 --> 00:03:04.160
from butterfly to moth, because that doesn't really make sense.

00:03:04.160 --> 00:03:08.000
And then also stochastic block model. This is a phrase I'm going to use a bunch, and

00:03:08.000 --> 00:03:13.520
I'm also going to abbreviate it as SBM. And this is simply just a network model that clusters

00:03:13.520 --> 00:03:19.440
nodes into blocks of nodes. And these nodes are grouped by the similarity of their edges.

00:03:19.440 --> 00:03:23.979
So in this example, we have this red cluster right here, and it's characterized by connections

00:03:23.979 --> 00:03:28.919
within itself. So all of the nodes tend to connect to nodes that are in the same cluster.

00:03:28.919 --> 00:03:34.360
The same thing goes for the blue. And all that needs to be known about a given node

00:03:34.360 --> 00:03:41.440
is what block it is in and what the connection propensities of that block are.

00:03:41.440 --> 00:03:45.720
So because I exist in academia right now, and if you don't show an equation in your

00:03:45.720 --> 00:03:50.199
talk, people assume that you don't know what you're talking about. So this is just the

00:03:50.199 --> 00:03:56.679
actual equation that governs this whole stochastic block model. And it's quite simple, even though

00:03:56.679 --> 00:04:02.039
there's a lot of Greek letters going on. But basically, you just need to know the data,

00:04:02.039 --> 00:04:06.880
which in this case is A, and that comes in the form of edges between nodes, which node

00:04:06.880 --> 00:04:13.080
each group, or what group each node belongs to, and then a matrix of the expected edge

00:04:13.080 --> 00:04:16.880
counts between those groups, which I was talking about earlier, is the propensity.

00:04:16.880 --> 00:04:20.519
And then you might notice, if you're familiar with some statistical formulas, that this

00:04:20.519 --> 00:04:25.799
looks very familiar. And that's because it's simply a Poisson model. So Poisson models

00:04:25.799 --> 00:04:31.239
model counts based on a parameter that is the average expected number of counts. And

00:04:31.239 --> 00:04:35.440
so in this case, the number of edges from a node to another node is governed by this

00:04:35.480 --> 00:04:42.000
Poisson distribution, where the propensity or lambda value is what is learned in the

00:04:42.000 --> 00:04:43.799
model.

00:04:43.799 --> 00:04:48.839
So really why I showed this equation is that a few years ago, I got the Poisson distribution

00:04:48.839 --> 00:04:53.679
tattooed on my arm. And I did that because I really just liked it. I thought it was a

00:04:53.679 --> 00:04:58.799
cool, elegant distribution. And little did I know that I would be spending the next couple

00:04:58.799 --> 00:05:04.959
years of my life intimately familiar and sort of hating the equation.

00:05:04.959 --> 00:05:11.760
So why stochastic block models? So in my research, we lurk a lot with electronic health

00:05:11.760 --> 00:05:17.000
records, or EHR data. And so with this type of data, questions that often arise are things

00:05:17.000 --> 00:05:21.720
like, who are these people similar to and why? So we might go to a collaborator, and

00:05:21.720 --> 00:05:26.040
they would have that question of, I'm interested in patients with type 2 diabetes. Can you

00:05:26.040 --> 00:05:30.640
show me other patients that are similar to them and tell me why they're similar?

00:05:30.679 --> 00:05:36.679
So the first thing that I tried was deep learning methods. So these worked well, but they had

00:05:36.679 --> 00:05:40.359
a couple of problems. And one is that they lacked interpretability. It could tell you

00:05:40.359 --> 00:05:44.519
that these nodes were similar to each other, but it wouldn't tell you why it said that.

00:05:44.519 --> 00:05:49.000
You can get that out of the model, but it's a little bit hard. And it needed specialization

00:05:49.000 --> 00:05:52.559
for these networks that have multipartite structure.

00:05:52.559 --> 00:05:56.720
And then also, we wanted a method that acknowledges the limitations of the data. So statisticians

00:05:56.720 --> 00:06:01.279
were very interested in uncertainty. And neural networks, again, there are kind of

00:06:01.279 --> 00:06:04.880
ways that you can get uncertainty out of them, but they are not fundamentally built with

00:06:04.880 --> 00:06:08.279
that idea in mind.

00:06:08.279 --> 00:06:12.920
So next is, why would I write a package to do this? And so there's a package in Python

00:06:12.920 --> 00:06:17.600
called GraphTool. And it fits stochastic block models. But there's a few issues with why

00:06:17.600 --> 00:06:22.239
we didn't use it. One is that my lab that I work in uses R exclusively. So every time

00:06:22.239 --> 00:06:26.079
I would show them Python code, people's eyes would glaze over.

00:06:26.079 --> 00:06:31.739
We're also quite focused on uncertainty. And GraphTool is great, but it doesn't focus quite

00:06:31.739 --> 00:06:37.119
on uncertainty as heavily as we would like. We also needed to tweak the underlying methods

00:06:37.119 --> 00:06:41.920
to optimize it for these bipartite networks. And I wanted to present at RStudio conference,

00:06:41.920 --> 00:06:45.299
and I couldn't do that if I wrote a Python package.

00:06:45.299 --> 00:06:51.119
So we'll get into the process now. So with every R package and really every kind of research

00:06:51.119 --> 00:06:54.559
project that someone does, you kind of got to get to the starting line. And honestly,

00:06:54.559 --> 00:06:56.820
that's the hardest part most of the time.

00:06:56.820 --> 00:07:01.279
And so for this project, there were kind of two things we had to do. And one was look

00:07:01.279 --> 00:07:06.600
into possible graph libraries. So we decided we wanted to use R to do this graph manipulation.

00:07:06.600 --> 00:07:12.559
So we looked at the elephant in the room is iGraph. And iGraph is a great package. However,

00:07:12.559 --> 00:07:17.679
much like GraphTool, it does a lot more than what we needed it to. And I don't know if

00:07:17.679 --> 00:07:22.459
you've ever tried to install a package that depends on iGraph, but it is a pain.

00:07:22.459 --> 00:07:27.579
And also, we wanted to add these kind of computationally heavy steps, something we'll illustrate later.

00:07:27.579 --> 00:07:32.320
And we had to do that in R by virtue of wrapping a package. And that kind of brought everything

00:07:32.320 --> 00:07:34.440
to a halt.

00:07:34.440 --> 00:07:39.200
And if you're more interested in kind of this tradeoff of adding a dependency versus writing

00:07:39.200 --> 00:07:44.239
stuff from scratch, I'd really encourage you to look at Jim Hester's It Depends talk from

00:07:44.239 --> 00:07:47.799
last year's RStudio, where he kind of talks about how big of a difference taking away

00:07:47.799 --> 00:07:52.239
one dependency can make in the uptake of your package in terms of, you know, does it take

00:07:52.239 --> 00:07:55.559
five hours to download or does it take five seconds?

00:07:55.559 --> 00:08:00.239
So after that, we decided that we were going to use Rcpp. And Rcpp, as you might know,

00:08:00.239 --> 00:08:06.000
is kind of a nice interface between R and C++ code. And it really just lets you write

00:08:06.000 --> 00:08:10.880
C++ code to do what you want. And then you can wire it up to R extremely easily.

00:08:11.000 --> 00:08:14.799
So this low-level interface kind of allowed us to get really close to the metal and keep

00:08:14.799 --> 00:08:18.899
it nice and memory efficient. We didn't want to keep, you know, pull around a bunch of

00:08:18.899 --> 00:08:25.959
extra data with our model such that we were wasting a lot of bits. And we also wanted

00:08:25.959 --> 00:08:31.640
to make sure our processing was nice and efficient. We didn't want to, you know, waste excess

00:08:31.640 --> 00:08:36.280
flops on things that weren't necessary for what we were doing.

00:08:36.280 --> 00:08:42.000
So once you've kind of gotten a package started, the next step and, you know, in research,

00:08:42.000 --> 00:08:47.679
the next step is doing tests. And so this kind of, I think about this in two ways. So

00:08:47.679 --> 00:08:51.719
from one, we come from the software side of things. And software side of things, this

00:08:51.719 --> 00:08:56.080
comes in the form of unit tests. So unit tests are these nice toy examples that you kind

00:08:56.080 --> 00:09:00.640
of break the problem down as simple as possible. You try to probe, you know, the limits of

00:09:00.640 --> 00:09:05.200
the problem, find the edge cases, and make sure that your software behaves as you think

00:09:05.200 --> 00:09:11.479
it should. And so this can benefit the statistics side of things by building strong foundations

00:09:11.479 --> 00:09:16.359
for larger models. If you're really sure that the model works in these kind of minimal examples,

00:09:16.359 --> 00:09:21.080
you're going to be confident about it scaling up. And then it also builds intuition about

00:09:21.080 --> 00:09:27.000
behavior. So, you know, kind of with these, you know, graph-based models, there's a lot

00:09:27.000 --> 00:09:30.520
of intuition that goes on behind it. And when you kind of code those minimal examples, you

00:09:30.520 --> 00:09:35.679
can gain that intuition pretty well. And then from the other side, when you do a statistics

00:09:35.679 --> 00:09:40.719
methods project, a lot of times you have to build one. You really should be doing simulated

00:09:40.719 --> 00:09:46.840
data. And so this can actually help the software side of things, I think, quite well because

00:09:46.840 --> 00:09:50.799
when you have simulated data, it's stochastic by definition, and it's going to find your

00:09:50.799 --> 00:09:56.359
edge cases, right? You will never be able to fully probe kind of the limits of your

00:09:56.359 --> 00:10:02.280
functions with just unit tests. But stochastic data, if there's a bug that you found, it

00:10:02.280 --> 00:10:06.320
will be found in, you know, one of the thousand times that you simulate data. This happened

00:10:06.320 --> 00:10:10.479
many, many times. And it also gives you an idea of real-world performance, so you don't

00:10:10.479 --> 00:10:14.799
kind of get sucked down a rabbit hole of thinking your stuff works really well when you have

00:10:14.799 --> 00:10:18.760
maybe an O of N squared operation hidden somewhere that doesn't show up until you start using

00:10:18.760 --> 00:10:25.080
big data. So kind of carrying on with the idea of speed,

00:10:25.080 --> 00:10:29.880
the next step a lot of times is kind of speeding stuff up. This is more of a software side

00:10:29.880 --> 00:10:35.239
of things. But one thing that you'll quickly learn if you start writing a package to do

00:10:35.239 --> 00:10:40.080
modeling is that the exact equations that you read in a paper or whatever are not going

00:10:40.080 --> 00:10:45.880
to be efficient. And so the example in this package is that we have this. This is the

00:10:45.880 --> 00:10:49.599
entropy of the model, which is essentially as the negative log likelihood, if you're

00:10:49.599 --> 00:10:55.119
familiar with those terms. Basically, we want this number to be as small as possible.

00:10:55.119 --> 00:10:58.440
And one of the things that we do is we move a node to another group, and we test how much

00:10:58.440 --> 00:11:03.239
this value changes. And if you do this whole thing, it's a very computationally expensive

00:11:03.239 --> 00:11:08.840
task. But you might notice, if you kind of dig into it and tear the equation apart, you

00:11:08.840 --> 00:11:11.880
know, different parts of it don't actually change, and so you don't need to calculate

00:11:11.880 --> 00:11:17.080
them. We have this divide by 2 here because we're double counting using this formula,

00:11:17.080 --> 00:11:22.679
so we can really optimize the equation. And by really digging into this, we actually

00:11:22.679 --> 00:11:27.239
have to think about what's going on a little bit more deep than you might necessarily do

00:11:27.239 --> 00:11:34.679
if you're just sitting there writing one off R scripts or writing math on a page.

00:11:34.679 --> 00:11:41.080
So kind of taking a step back also for the test side of things, this documentation serves

00:11:41.080 --> 00:11:50.599
as a test in a way, too. So as you write these, as you do this research, and you're

00:11:50.599 --> 00:11:54.919
constantly updating your documentation over that process, it keeps you focused on the

00:11:54.919 --> 00:11:59.000
big picture. And so this is nice because you don't, like I said before, you don't want

00:11:59.000 --> 00:12:04.559
to, you know, get stuck right in the unit test, working little toy examples, open it

00:12:04.559 --> 00:12:08.719
up to the real world, and then you start having problems where any time you run it with something

00:12:08.719 --> 00:12:14.119
over 100 nodes, it takes a million years to run. And it can serve as an informal sniff

00:12:14.119 --> 00:12:18.719
test for results. So this picture on the right is an example of I was, you know, working

00:12:18.719 --> 00:12:22.239
with some data, and it kept on having these really big drops. And I was like, what is

00:12:22.239 --> 00:12:26.400
going on? And it was actually dropping into negative values, which is something that shouldn't

00:12:26.400 --> 00:12:31.880
be possible. And by digging into that, all my tests were passing, all of the different

00:12:31.880 --> 00:12:35.320
tests, you know, all the behavior that I was thinking about was working. But I actually

00:12:35.320 --> 00:12:39.159
found a bug in the logic of the code from looking at this. And I wouldn't have caught

00:12:39.159 --> 00:12:46.239
that if I wasn't constantly updating the documentation and looking at how things were changing.

00:12:46.239 --> 00:12:52.479
So another mildly selfish part of this thing is writing vignettes. And I think about this

