So now moving on to the kind of last part, which is the actual product that this whole

00:13:44.320 --> 00:13:50.580
process has been leading up to. And so quickly taking a step back to reorient ourselves,

00:13:50.580 --> 00:13:55.679
what exactly is SBMR? And that's a tentative name for the package. It probably will change.

00:13:55.679 --> 00:14:02.119
It's not very creative. But it's a native R package, kind of, right? It uses C++ code.

00:14:02.119 --> 00:14:09.119
But thanks to RCPP, it's essentially native at this point. And it's stochastic block models.

00:14:09.119 --> 00:14:14.000
And its primary focus is investigating the uncertainty of the found structure by sampling

00:14:14.000 --> 00:14:18.280
from the Bayesian posterior. So if you're familiar with Bayesian models, you can get

00:14:18.280 --> 00:14:24.000
uncertainty by looking at the posterior distribution. That's how we get uncertainty in this clustering.

