00:17:53.479 --> 00:18:00.079
clusters because we simulated three clusters. So the first thing that you want to do whenever

00:18:00.079 --> 00:18:03.920
you're doing Bayesian sampling is if you're going to sample from a posterior, you want

00:18:03.920 --> 00:18:08.959
to get as close to the optimal starting point as possible. And this is because when the

00:18:08.959 --> 00:18:14.880
posterior sampling, you could spend a lot of time kind of getting to equilibrium. And

00:18:14.880 --> 00:18:20.479
so you might be familiar with the concept of burning in a chain, which is where you

00:18:20.479 --> 00:18:25.160
kind of let it run for a while until it finds its natural resting point. And then you start

00:18:25.160 --> 00:18:29.719
sampling. But that's kind of an inexact science. And so we have an algorithm built into the

00:18:29.719 --> 00:18:34.400
package that does agglomerative merging. So it basically takes every node, starts it

00:18:34.400 --> 00:18:40.640
in its own cluster, and then slowly merges those clusters together one by one until you

00:18:40.640 --> 00:18:45.839
have one node. And it records the model fit. So in this entropy value. And so higher value

00:18:45.839 --> 00:18:53.079
is worse fit. And so what we're really looking for here is kind of the point where clusters,

00:18:53.079 --> 00:18:57.040
true clusters start being merged together because the model says I have to take these

00:18:57.040 --> 00:19:01.199
three clusters and merge them into two. So it had to kind of merge two clusters that

00:19:01.199 --> 00:19:06.760
were not able to be merged in reality. And so ideally, there will be a sharp kind of

00:19:06.760 --> 00:19:16.160
decrease, increase in model penalty for that change. And so we have this heuristic for

00:19:16.160 --> 00:19:20.280
detecting that point, which we call the delta ratio is something that we've developed. It's

00:19:20.280 --> 00:19:26.880
not particularly important. But we can see that right here, we've very clearly picked

00:19:26.880 --> 00:19:32.040
out this point of three clusters, which is what we know. I drew a line here to say, you

00:19:32.040 --> 00:19:36.479
know, we know that there are three clusters. How does it tell us? And so very clearly,

00:19:36.479 --> 00:19:40.199
the model has said, I think that there are three clusters in your data. And so let me

00:19:40.199 --> 00:19:45.199
choose that. And so we can do a sanity check because we know what actually generated the

00:19:45.199 --> 00:19:51.959
data. And so conveniently, we actually perfectly separated our clusters, right? So this is

00:19:51.959 --> 00:19:56.560
the simulated block of the node. And this is the inferred block. And so what we see

00:19:56.560 --> 00:20:02.359
is that every single inferred block perfectly corresponds to the data generating block.

00:20:02.359 --> 00:20:07.119
And this algorithm honestly works incredibly well. It's, you could really, if you wanted

00:20:07.119 --> 00:20:13.319
to just do all of your inference in this model without going to the Bayesian values, you

00:20:13.319 --> 00:20:17.319
could do pretty well. It does surprisingly well.

00:20:17.319 --> 00:20:26.160
So once we have that kind of equilibriated posterior situation, we can do MCMC sweeps.

00:20:26.160 --> 00:20:32.719
And so we can just pipe our model object to this function MCMC sweep, tell it how many

00:20:32.719 --> 00:20:37.119
sweeps we want to do. We give it an epsilon value. And epsilon, in this case, is an ergodicity

00:20:37.119 --> 00:20:43.280
parameter. So it kind of influences how random your choices of different nodes are. So, you

00:20:43.280 --> 00:20:48.079
know, when a node is sitting and being checked in a sweep, how likely it is to be, you know,

00:20:48.079 --> 00:20:51.880
given to just a random group rather than one that follows the data.

00:20:51.880 --> 00:20:55.400
And we also have this interesting value called track peers here that we'll get into in two

00:20:55.400 --> 00:21:00.319
seconds. But what we can see is that we have a very stable chain. And honestly, that's

00:21:00.319 --> 00:21:04.920
because it's perfectly equilibriated, right? We know exactly where it is and it perfectly

00:21:04.920 --> 00:21:08.959
fit there. And we get a little bit of variation as we go over our sweeps, as the number of

00:21:08.959 --> 00:21:13.640
nodes moved. But everything is working pretty well.

00:21:13.640 --> 00:21:17.479
So, you know, that's fine. But what we're interested in is looking at the uncertainty

00:21:17.479 --> 00:21:23.000
in this clustering. And so when we do that track pairs option, what it does is it keeps

00:21:23.000 --> 00:21:28.839
track internally at every single sweep. It says, you know, these two nodes, are they

00:21:28.839 --> 00:21:34.680
in the same cluster internally? And then as we do our sweeps, we just keep tallying up

00:21:34.680 --> 00:21:41.119
that value. And that gives us this kind of consensus matrix. And that will tell us, so,

00:21:41.119 --> 00:21:46.640
right, blue is, you know, 100% of the time we were in the same group. And so we can aggregate

00:21:46.640 --> 00:21:51.319
all of these MCMZ sweeps to get an idea of the kind of stability of our network.

00:21:51.319 --> 00:21:55.920
And so this is an easy way to see it. However, you know, this is nice and got little nice

00:21:55.920 --> 00:21:59.680
triangles here. And that's because we know the true structure. So what if we don't know

00:21:59.680 --> 00:22:02.839
the true structure, so we can't sort it? Because if we didn't have this sorted, it would look

00:22:02.839 --> 00:22:08.199
kind of, you know, it'd be hard to tell unless we knew the true sorting of the network.

00:22:08.199 --> 00:22:13.479
So we have a new thing that we're calling consensus SNE. So you might be familiar with

00:22:13.479 --> 00:22:17.959
t-SNE, which is t-distributed stochastic neighbor embedding. We're calling this consensus

00:22:17.959 --> 00:22:23.760
SNE. It's a totally made-up name that I just did today. But it's basically taking these

00:22:23.760 --> 00:22:28.920
propensities and building a network between nodes where the node is connected to another

00:22:29.040 --> 00:22:35.280
node if it is, you know, follows some threshold of connection. And so what we can see is with

00:22:35.280 --> 00:22:41.800
our data, and I'll refresh this again, it perfectly separates itself into the component

00:22:41.800 --> 00:22:46.479
clusters that we generated. And what you'll see is in, you know, less certain models,

00:22:46.479 --> 00:22:50.479
there might be some connections between, so you get the hierarchical structure without

00:22:50.479 --> 00:22:55.079
having to, you know, figure out how to sort your heat map.

00:22:55.079 --> 00:22:59.599
So I have very little time left, but the future plans, we're going to focus a little

00:22:59.599 --> 00:23:05.040
bit more on node-level uncertainty to allow us to try to find, you know, outlier nodes,

00:23:05.040 --> 00:23:09.920
values that don't really fit the generating distribution that we've inferred. And we're

00:23:09.920 --> 00:23:13.560
also going to just put a lot more visualizations. I've been working on this product for a long

00:23:13.560 --> 00:23:17.760
time, and I have lots of visualization ideas, and I want to kind of start pumping them out

00:23:17.760 --> 00:23:23.719
now that we've got the fundamental kernel going on. And just a quick thanks. So to my

00:23:23.719 --> 00:23:29.599
advisor, Yao-Min Zhu, at Vanderbilt, lab biostatistician, Siyue Zhang, who's been

00:23:29.599 --> 00:23:33.520
working with me on this, and the other lab members for their thoughtful comments during

00:23:33.520 --> 00:23:38.479
the whole process. I'm supported by the Vanderbilt Biostatistics Development Grant. And most

00:23:38.479 --> 00:23:42.520
importantly, my cat has been very helpful all the days that I banged my head against

00:23:42.520 --> 00:23:47.520
the wall. While I couldn't figure out some bug, he was there, and I guess, you know,

00:23:47.520 --> 00:23:50.479
my wife was there, too, to help me out. So thank you very much.

00:23:53.719 --> 00:23:54.979
Thank you.

